Introduction

Indiana state forests today are a reminder of what Indiana’s land looked like before settlers moved in and started replacing trees with crops. Logging in the early 1900s changed the landscape dramatically. What were once lush, tall forests were flattened. Indiana's vast wetlands were paved over to create paths for easy travel.

By 19XX, most of the forest was gone, with only XX percent remaining. Concerned Hoosiers set aside land in 1932 (was it a law enacted?) to be used as a resource for future generations. Recently, with the state’s growing emphasis on budget tightening, priorities have changed. State forest logging has increased 1000 percent in the last decade, prompting a battle over how to manage these forests.

Owen-Putnam State Forest:

2153 Fishcreek Rd. Spencer, IN 47460

(812) 829-2462

There has part of the best hardwood forests in the United States and deer, squirrel and turkey hunting. Based on the north-south orientation, there has a pond has fish in it, and also has a grand view of nature for around 50 foot. The forest has the Forest Office, Fish Creek Campground, Horse Campground and Rattlesnake Campground.

Yellowwood State forest:

772 South Yellowwood RoadNashville, IN 47448

(812) 988-7945

Yellowwood State Forest was created in 1940 when federal land was leased to the state of Indiana. There has more than 2,000 abandoned and eroded acres were planted to pine (red, jack, shortleaf, white and scotch), black locust, black walnut, white and red oak.

Yellowwood Lake was completed in 1939. It has 133-acre lake and about 30 feet deep.

Logging supporters, led by Governor Pence and the state’s own forestry department, argue logging provides jobs, revenue and can be managed effectively. Trees grow back, after all, The DOF says they carefully select the trees to be cut and employ responsible foresters to monitor the loggers. They are quick to report that state forest logging has reaped on average $2.5(check?) million a year since Governor Daniels initiated the increase.

But a growing number of protesters say the spreadsheet tells a one-sided story. They ask Hoosiers to consider the less easily quantifiable costs— damage to roads from logging trucks, a loss of tourism and an eventual decrease in property values. Opponents argue that even in strictly financial terms, the current bid system is undercutting landowners and privately owned tree farms. They say it is driving down timber prices and will hurt Indiana’s second (?) most profitable(?) industry in the long run.

Perhaps the most elusive cost is the value of going into the forest. What number can someone put on the feeling of standing below a 100-year-old oak tree and looking up? A family’s walk along the paths of Yellowwood in the fall? Proponents argue damage to forests’ sensitive ecology could be irreversible. In a worst-case scenario, opponents say wildlife will leave the forest and not return. Invasive species will take over where healthy trees once grew, destroying the forest’s canopy. Indiana will deplete one of its most valued assets, free to any hiker, hunter or camper with the mind to go there. Forestry officials say these scenarios are simply scare tactics. The forest changes they seek will increase the diversity and reduce invasive species that harm the forest while still making much need revenue and provide Indiana with much need employment.

IU’s immersive journalism class talked to the stakeholders — foresters, environmentalists, politicians and every-day Hoosiers. They looked at the spreadsheets and reported not just the totals, but what the stakeholders had to say about the process behind the bidding. Here’s what they learned.
